(59, 1, '2015-11-22 04:22:24', '2015-11-22 04:22:24', '<h2> How To Become A Great Mentor </h2>\r\n\r\n\r\nThe mediocre teacher tells. The good teacher explains. The superior teacher demonstrates. The great teacher inspires. - William Arthur Ward\r\n\r\nHave you employed a mentor to help you navigate the professional world? Maybe you found her during your first job search; perhaps it was when you transitioned careers. Either wayâ€”your mentor most likely provided guidance and helped you overcome challenges. And if youâ€™re really lucky, she inspired you along the way.\r\n\r\nAccording to David Parnell, a legal consultant, communication coach and author, when it comes to mentorship, it is an unwritten rule that â€œone should give back at least what theyâ€™ve received.â€\r\n\r\nSo, if youâ€™ve ever had a mentor, you might want to think about paying it forward.\r\n\r\nâ€œMentoringâ€”or at minimum connecting with a variety of people in all industries and age groupsâ€”has never been more important,â€ says Pamela Ryckman, author of Stiletto Network: Inside the Womenâ€™s Power Circles That Are Changing the Face of Business.\r\n\r\nBut itâ€™s a big responsibility.\r\n\r\nA mentor must believe in her mentee, both personally and professionally, Ryckman explains. â€œMentors help fill your knowledge gaps and seek opportunities to help you grow and excel. A mentor is someone with whom you can let down your guard, share your insecurities, and ask the â€˜stupidâ€™ questions we all have sometimes.â€\r\n\r\nA great mentor also sees her mentee as a person, not just an employee. She knows enough about their personal life to understand the external factors that impact their work, and cares about their happiness. â€œA [great] mentor is honest and unafraid to tell you hard truths about yourself and your work,â€ Ryckman adds. â€œShe helps you navigate the politics of your organization or profession, and avoid the land mines. She pushes you to take risks and aim higher, and advocates for you when youâ€™re not there.â€\r\n\r\nThereâ€™s a lot of personal satisfaction that comes from watching someone you care about reach his full potential. But as it turns out, mentoring goes far beyond that.\r\n\r\nâ€œHelping someone else succeed can be immensely gratifying,â€ Ryckman says. â€œBut what Iâ€™ve heard time and again from executive â€˜eldersâ€™ is how much they gain in return when they mentor young people. Theyâ€™re often surprised at how much they learn from their mentees. Mentoring really goes both ways; when different generations come together, their blend of skills can be highly complementary.â€\r\n\r\nRyan Kahn, a career coach, founder of The Hired Group, star of MTVâ€™s Hired, and author of Hired! The Guide for the Recent Grad, adds: â€œBy investing in others youâ€™re also investing in yourself. For example, as you move forward in your career, youâ€™ll need to be able to identify and recruit fresh talent. Having a strong network of mentees can help you find and grow these rising stars.â€\r\n\r\nWant to become a great mentor? Here are 9 things youâ€™ll need to do:\r\n\r\nAlways play both roles. Ideally, one would never have to make the transition from mentee to mentor, Ryckman says. â€œWe should all be learning from others (playing the mentee role) and teaching others (being the mentor) throughout our careers.â€\r\n\r\nBe committed.  Being a mentor is a commitment, Kahn says. â€œIf youâ€™re offering to help someone you need to follow through with that promise by being there for them when needed.â€\r\n\r\nKnow that your mentee can be anyone, anywhere. â€œMentoring neednâ€™t follow the traditional â€˜elder-upstartâ€™ prescription anymore. It can be peer-to-peer across functions or industries,â€ Rychman says. â€œItâ€™s about supplementing skill gaps and helping each person learn and grow.â€\r\n\r\nAs a mentor, youâ€™re someone who knows something your mentee doesnâ€™t, and you care enough to help them learn and succeed.\r\n\r\nâ€œToday, industries overlap and are interdependent in ways that were inconceivable a decade ago, and employees can no longer afford to stay stuck in a particular silo, oblivious to developments in other fields,â€ she says. â€œCompanies have realized that when people from different backgrounds with varying skills convene to debate and brainstorm, advances occur. In the â€˜new,â€™ conceptual economy, the ability to draw knowledge from diverse spheres is prized.â€\r\n\r\nListen. One of your jobs a mentor is to provide advice and encouragement, but in order to do so, you need to make the time to listen and understand the situation, Kahn says.\r\n\r\nâ€œIntently listening to a mentee as they vent and, ideally, sort their way through confusion, is often more than enough to get them through the day,â€ Parnell says. â€œIf you ask any therapist about the power of listening, they will tell you the same thing: It is massive. Any mentor that is worth their weight spends considerably more time listening than they do speaking.â€\r\n\r\nHave your own mentor(s) and network. Today, the most successful people build relationships and gather intelligence from a wide variety of experts in all industries and age brackets, Rychman says. â€œPeople who are insularâ€”who always return to the same small circle for advice and supportâ€”become closed off from opportunities.â€ In order to be the very best mentor, you need to continue building your network and taking advice from those you trust.\r\n\r\nBe open-minded and compassionate. â€œIf youâ€™ve ever argued with someone, you know that they will never see your side until theyâ€™re convinced that youâ€™ve seen theirs,â€ Parnell says. â€œAnd to provide valuable guidance and advice that is well received, it is necessary to first understand the menteeâ€™s needs, wants, feelings, et cetera. This can only come in the form of deep and implicit empathy.â€\r\n\r\nHave patience. Much like parenting, mentoring can be a satisfying, but also long-term and trying, endeavor, Parnell 